{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ebaaad5e-2637-4966-bf79-e41c5cda72a9","content":"Use **dotnet-trace** — it's the simplest option for .NET apps and doesn't require installing heavy tools like PerfView or ETW.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (runs until you press Enter)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### If you need OS-level detail too:\n\nUse **dotnet-trace** with the `--format speedscope` flag to get a flame graph viewable at [speedscope.app](https://speedscope.app), or use **PerfView** for deeper ETW-based analysis:\n\n```powershell\n# PerfView (download from GitHub)\nPerfView.exe collect /ThreadTime /CircularMB:500\n```\n\n**Recommendation:** Start with `dotnet-trace` — it's lightweight, .NET-aware, and gives you managed call stacks with minimal overhead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"40fdd6de-3d95-491c-a021-d26b9f08c843","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":336},"id":"099b549a-ef6f-473e-be5c-f641fb5a76ac","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:48:54.551Z","parentId":"50e604fd-3458-4587-b9b0-b9c51dbec7a7"}
